{"summary":"Reviewed the referenced code paths and all five amendments identify valid issues or worthwhile maintainability improvements. Four are straightforward accepts, and the timeout-classification amendment should also be accepted because the current code conflates timeout cause with teardown-confirmation state, which changes retry semantics and loses timeout-specific handling downstream.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-21-7297fd7b","decision":"accept","rationale":"The timeout-detection match is duplicated verbatim in two nearby error paths. That heuristic is already subtle because it has to recognize both clean Timeout failures and timeout messages carried as TransportFailure details. Extracting a single helper reduces drift risk and improves maintainability with negligible implementation risk."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-093a1416","decision":"accept","rationale":"An invocation that exceeded its deadline is still fundamentally a timeout; whether teardown was confirmed is additional state, not a different primary failure cause. Encoding unconfirmed teardown by switching the failure class to TransportFailure changes the retry budget, bypasses timeout-specific mapping in higher layers, and forces other code to recover timeout semantics indirectly from the details string. A dedicated variant or separate teardown flag would model this more correctly and robustly."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-0153f5fb","decision":"accept","rationale":"`spawn_background_reap` currently calls `child.wait().await` with no bound, and `ManagedChild::wait()` polls forever until the process exits. If the process cannot be reaped promptly, that task holds the `Arc<ManagedChild>` indefinitely and never completes. Adding a timeout and then logging plus dropping the handle is an appropriate containment fix for a real resource-leak scenario."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-eeb662d0","decision":"accept","rationale":"`fail_run()` now treats snapshot persistence as best-effort, but `resume_run_with_retry_internal()` rejects snapshots that still say `Running` before it consults journal-derived resume state. If snapshot writes keep failing, the journal records the failure while `run.json` remains stale, and resume is blocked permanently. That is a real recoverability bug unless resume/status/start paths fall back to journal state when the snapshot is stale."},{"amendment_id":"fr-21-451f4174","decision":"accept","rationale":"The process adapter only signals the direct child PID and considers teardown confirmed once that PID exits. Because the command is not isolated into its own process group/session, any helper processes it spawned can survive the timeout and continue running untracked while retries proceed. That is a real process-lifecycle defect; tearing down the full process tree and testing the orphan-helper case is the right direction."}]}